[{"id":"VH605681","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH605679.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following best explains the continuity in the trade routes between East Africa, the Arabian Peninsula, and India as shown on the maps?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH605681_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Map 1</span></p></div></div><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a map titled “Major Trading Routes, Circa 1250 to 1450 C.E.” Africa, southern Europe, Asia, Australia, and Oceania are shown. Land-based trade routes crisscross North Africa, Central Asia, and South Asia, and connect these to East Asia. Sea-based trade routes cross the Mediterranean, connect West Africa to Western Europe, and connect the whole East African and Arabian coastlines with the whole South and East Asian coastlines, with connections to ports in Indonesia, the Philippines, and Japan as well.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH605679.g08.png\"/></div><div class=\"passage\"><div class=\"prose style:1\"><p class=\"passage_para\"><span class=\"formatted_text text_decoration:underline\">Map 2</span></p></div></div><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a map titled “Major Trading Routes, Circa 1450 to 1750 C.E.” Africa, southern Europe, Asia, Australia, and Oceania are shown. Land-based trade routes crisscross North Africa, Central Asia, and South Asia, and connect these to East Asia. Sea-based trade routes crisscross the Mediterranean, extend from Europe along the West African coastline, pass the tip of Southern Africa, criscross the Indian Ocean, connecting to points along the East African coastline, the Indian subcontinent, and many points in Southeast Asia and Oceania. Additional sea-based trade routes can also be seen leaving westward from Europe across the Atlantic Ocean and leaving eastward from Asia across the Pacific Ocean.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH605679.g10.png\"/></div></div>"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Trade along the routes depended on the activities of Chinese merchants.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Trade along the routes relied on sailors’ knowledge of the monsoon winds.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Trade along the routes depended on silver from the Americas.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Trade along the routes relied on sailors’ knowledge of longitude from classical maps.</p>"],"answer":1}]